Note: ===================================================================
Note: HIR TO PHP CODE GENERATOR
Note: ===================================================================
Note: Generates PHP code from High-level Intermediate Representation (HIR).

Note: Part of the Translation Translation System
Note: Location: compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/php/hir_to_php.runa
Note: ===================================================================

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIR

Note: ===================================================================
Note: GENERATION CONTEXT
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The per-translation working context for the PHP code generator. The
output string accumulates all emitted PHP source; indent_level tracks
the current nesting depth so emit_indent can prefix lines with the
right number of spaces. current_namespace is reserved for future
namespace-aware emission (PHP 'namespace' / 'use' directives).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Runa struct of three fields: output (running String of generated PHP),
indent_level (Integer, 0-based), current_namespace (String, currently
unused but kept for forward compatibility). Constructed via
create_generation_context with empty strings and zero indent.
@End Implementation
Type called "GenerationContext":
    output as Integer
    indent_level as Integer
    current_namespace as Integer
End Type

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MAIN GENERATION ENTRY POINT
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver: creates a fresh GenerationContext, prefixes the
output with the PHP open tag '<?php', and dispatches to
generate_module. Returns the accumulated output string so the caller
can write it to a file or pass it on.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls create_generation_context to obtain a fresh ctx. Emits the
"<?php\n\n" header. Calls generate_module(ctx, hir_module). Returns
ctx.output (the String built up by every emit call).
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_php_from_hir" takes hir_module as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx be proc create_generation_context
    
    Note: Add PHP opening tag
    proc emit with ctx, "<?php\n\n"
    
    proc generate_module with ctx, hir_module
    
    Return ctx.output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for GenerationContext. Initialises every field to a safe
empty value so the caller can immediately begin emitting without
checking for null slots. The initial indent_level of 0 is correct
for module-level emission.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Constructs a GenerationContext with empty-string output, 0
indent_level, and empty-string current_namespace. Returns the new
value.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_generation_context" returns Integer:
    Let ctx be a value of type GenerationContext with
        output as "",
        indent_level as 0,
        current_namespace as ""
    
    Return ctx
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MODULE GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Walks the three top-level lists of an HIR module - imports, classes,
and functions - and emits each as a PHP top-level construct. The
order matters: 'use' directives must precede class/function bodies in
valid PHP. A blank line is inserted between sections only when the
preceding section was non-empty so the output is tidy regardless of
which sections are populated.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Queries HIR module accessors hir_module_get_imports/_classes/_functions.
Each section's list is iterated by index; per item the corresponding
generate_import / generate_class / generate_function is invoked. After
each non-empty section the routine emits a "\n" so the next section
starts on a fresh blank line.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_module" takes ctx as Integer, hir_module as Integer:
    Note: Generate imports
    Let imports be proc hir_module_get_imports from HIR with hir_module
    Let import_count be proc list_length from ListCore with imports
    Let i be 0
    
    While i is less than import_count:
        Let import_node be proc list_get from ListCore with imports, i
        proc generate_import with ctx, import_node
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    
    If import_count is greater than 0:
        proc emit with ctx, "\n"
    End If
    
    Note: Generate classes
    Let classes be proc hir_module_get_classes from HIR with hir_module
    Let class_count be proc list_length from ListCore with classes
    Set i to 0
    
    While i is less than class_count:
        Let class_node be proc list_get from ListCore with classes, i
        proc generate_class with ctx, class_node
        proc emit with ctx, "\n"
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    
    Note: Generate functions
    Let functions be proc hir_module_get_functions from HIR with hir_module
    Let func_count be proc list_length from ListCore with functions
    Set i to 0
    
    While i is less than func_count:
        Let func_node be proc list_get from ListCore with functions, i
        proc generate_function with ctx, func_node
        proc emit with ctx, "\n"
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: IMPORT GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emits a PHP 'use Name;' directive for each HIR import. PHP's 'use'
imports a namespace/class into the current file scope, the closest
analogue to a generic source-language import. Indentation is applied
even at module scope (0 indent) so the directive shape is uniform.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls hir_import_get_name to retrieve the import target string. Emits
"use ", then the name, then ";\n" - the trailing newline ensures each
'use' directive sits on its own line.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_import" takes ctx as Integer, import_node as Integer:
    Let import_name be proc hir_import_get_name from HIR with import_node
    
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "use "
    proc emit with ctx, import_name
    proc emit with ctx, ";\n"
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: CLASS GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emits a PHP class, interface, or trait declaration with all its
members. The discrimination among class/interface/trait is carried as
the metadata key 'php_type' on the HIR node so the same HIR shape
covers all three; this avoids three nearly-identical generators.
Modifiers (abstract/final), 'extends' parent, and 'implements' list
are also read from metadata. Inside the body, the four member kinds
are emitted in the conventional PHP order: constants, fields, then
methods - matching common PSR style guides.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads php_type, php_modifier, php_extends, php_implements via
hir_get_metadata. Emits modifier prefix (abstract/final), then
class/interface/trait keyword, then the class name, then optional
'extends X', then optional 'implements I1, I2'. Opens body brace.
Iterates hir_class_get_constants, _fields, _methods; each iteration
delegates to generate_class_constant / generate_field /
generate_method. A blank line separates non-empty member groups;
within methods a blank line separates adjacent methods. Closes body
brace.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_class" takes ctx as Integer, class_node as Integer:
    Let class_name be proc hir_class_get_name from HIR with class_node
    
    Note: Check if this is an interface or trait
    Let php_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with class_node, "php_type"
    
    Let is_interface be proc string_equals from StringCore with php_type, "interface"
    Let is_trait be proc string_equals from StringCore with php_type, "trait"
    
    Note: Extract modifiers
    Let modifiers be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with class_node, "php_modifier"
    
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    
    Note: Emit modifiers
    If modifiers is not equal to 0:
        Let is_abstract be proc string_equals from StringCore with modifiers, "abstract"
        Let is_final be proc string_equals from StringCore with modifiers, "final"
        
        If is_abstract is equal to 1:
            proc emit with ctx, "abstract "
        End If
        
        If is_final is equal to 1:
            proc emit with ctx, "final "
        End If
    End If
    
    Note: Emit class/interface/trait keyword
    If is_interface is equal to 1:
        proc emit with ctx, "interface "
    Otherwise:
        If is_trait is equal to 1:
            proc emit with ctx, "trait "
        Otherwise:
            proc emit with ctx, "class "
        End If
    End If
    
    proc emit with ctx, class_name
    
    Note: Emit extends
    Let extends_class be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with class_node, "php_extends"
    If extends_class is not equal to 0:
        Let extends_len be proc string_length from StringCore with extends_class
        If extends_len is greater than 0:
            proc emit with ctx, " extends "
            proc emit with ctx, extends_class
        End If
    End If
    
    Note: Emit implements
    Let implements_list be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with class_node, "php_implements"
    If implements_list is not equal to 0:
        Let implements_count be proc list_length from ListCore with implements_list
        If implements_count is greater than 0:
            proc emit with ctx, " implements "
            
            Let j be 0
            While j is less than implements_count:
                Let interface_name be proc list_get from ListCore with implements_list, j
                proc emit with ctx, interface_name
                
                If j is less than implements_count minus 1:
                    proc emit with ctx, ", "
                End If
                
                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
        End If
    End If
    
    proc emit with ctx, "\n"
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "{\n"
    
    proc increase_indent from ctx
    
    Note: Generate constants
    Let constants be proc hir_class_get_constants from HIR with class_node
    Let const_count be proc list_length from ListCore with constants
    Let i be 0
    
    While i is less than const_count:
        Let const_node be proc list_get from ListCore with constants, i
        proc generate_class_constant with ctx, const_node
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    
    If const_count is greater than 0:
        proc emit with ctx, "\n"
    End If
    
    Note: Generate fields
    Let fields be proc hir_class_get_fields from HIR with class_node
    Let field_count be proc list_length from ListCore with fields
    Set i to 0
    
    While i is less than field_count:
        Let field_node be proc list_get from ListCore with fields, i
        proc generate_field with ctx, field_node
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    
    If field_count is greater than 0:
        proc emit with ctx, "\n"
    End If
    
    Note: Generate methods
    Let methods be proc hir_class_get_methods from HIR with class_node
    Let method_count be proc list_length from ListCore with methods
    Set i to 0
    
    While i is less than method_count:
        Let method_node be proc list_get from ListCore with methods, i
        proc generate_method with ctx, method_node
        
        If i is less than method_count minus 1:
            proc emit with ctx, "\n"
        End If
        
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    
    proc decrease_indent from ctx
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "}\n"
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: CLASS MEMBER GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emits a PHP class-level constant declaration ('public const X = ...').
Class constants in PHP carry visibility (public/protected/private)
from PHP 7.1 onward; this generator emits the visibility from
metadata or defaults to 'public' for compatibility with older PHP
targets and PSR style.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads visibility from metadata; emits it (with a trailing space) or
"public " as fallback. Emits 'const NAME = '. Recurses into
generate_expression for the value initialiser. Terminates with ";\n".
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_class_constant" takes ctx as Integer, const_node as Integer:
    Let const_name be proc hir_constant_get_name from HIR with const_node
    
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    
    Note: Visibility
    Let visibility be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with const_node, "visibility"
    If visibility is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with ctx, visibility
        proc emit with ctx, " "
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with ctx, "public "
    End If
    
    proc emit with ctx, "const "
    proc emit with ctx, const_name
    proc emit with ctx, " = "
    
    Let value be proc hir_constant_get_value from HIR with const_node
    proc generate_expression with ctx, value
    
    proc emit with ctx, ";\n"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a PHP class property declaration. PHP property declarations
carry visibility, optional 'static', and optional default initialiser.
The field name in HIR omits the conventional '$' prefix used by PHP;
it is the caller's responsibility to ensure the name field already
includes the '$' if the target style requires it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads visibility, is_static, default_value from metadata. Emits
visibility (with fallback "public "). Emits "static " if applicable.
Emits the field_name. If default_value is non-null, emits " = " and
recurses into generate_expression. Terminates with ";\n".
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_field" takes ctx as Integer, field_node as Integer:
    Let field_name be proc hir_field_get_name from HIR with field_node
    
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    
    Note: Visibility
    Let visibility be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with field_node, "visibility"
    If visibility is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with ctx, visibility
        proc emit with ctx, " "
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with ctx, "public "
    End If
    
    Note: Static
    Let is_static be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with field_node, "is_static"
    If is_static is equal to 1:
        proc emit with ctx, "static "
    End If
    
    proc emit with ctx, field_name
    
    Note: Default value
    Let default_value be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with field_node, "default_value"
    If default_value is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with ctx, " = "
        proc generate_expression with ctx, default_value
    End If
    
    proc emit with ctx, ";\n"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a PHP method declaration. Covers the full PHP method modifier
set: visibility, static, abstract, final, plus an optional ':
return-type' tail. Abstract methods omit the body and terminate with
';' per PHP semantics; concrete methods follow the header with a
block body.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads name. Emits modifiers in PHP-canonical order: visibility,
static, abstract, final. Emits "function NAME(", then delegates to
generate_parameters for the comma-separated argument list, then ")".
If return_type metadata is non-empty, appends ": Type". For abstract
methods emits ";\n" only; for concrete methods emits "\n" and
recurses into generate_statement on the body.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_method" takes ctx as Integer, method_node as Integer:
    Let method_name be proc hir_function_get_name from HIR with method_node
    
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    
    Note: Visibility
    Let visibility be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with method_node, "visibility"
    If visibility is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with ctx, visibility
        proc emit with ctx, " "
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with ctx, "public "
    End If
    
    Note: Static
    Let is_static be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with method_node, "is_static"
    If is_static is equal to 1:
        proc emit with ctx, "static "
    End If
    
    Note: Abstract
    Let is_abstract be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with method_node, "is_abstract"
    If is_abstract is equal to 1:
        proc emit with ctx, "abstract "
    End If
    
    Note: Final
    Let is_final be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with method_node, "is_final"
    If is_final is equal to 1:
        proc emit with ctx, "final "
    End If
    
    proc emit with ctx, "function "
    proc emit with ctx, method_name
    proc emit with ctx, "("
    
    Note: Parameters
    proc generate_parameters with ctx, method_node
    
    proc emit with ctx, ")"
    
    Note: Return type
    Let return_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with method_node, "return_type"
    If return_type is not equal to 0:
        Let type_len be proc string_length from StringCore with return_type
        If type_len is greater than 0:
            proc emit with ctx, ": "
            proc emit with ctx, return_type
        End If
    End If
    
    Note: Abstract methods have no body
    If is_abstract is equal to 1:
        proc emit with ctx, ";\n"
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with ctx, "\n"
        
        Let body be proc hir_function_get_body from HIR with method_node
        proc generate_statement with ctx, body
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: FUNCTION GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emits a top-level PHP function declaration. Unlike methods, free
functions have no visibility modifier. Return-type metadata is honoured
identically to generate_method's tail. The body is always present
(PHP has no 'abstract function' at file scope).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads name. Emits "function NAME(", delegates to generate_parameters,
emits ")". If return_type metadata is non-empty, appends ": Type".
Emits "\n" then recurses into generate_statement on the body.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_function" takes ctx as Integer, func_node as Integer:
    Let func_name be proc hir_function_get_name from HIR with func_node
    
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "function "
    proc emit with ctx, func_name
    proc emit with ctx, "("
    
    Note: Parameters
    proc generate_parameters with ctx, func_node
    
    proc emit with ctx, ")"
    
    Note: Return type
    Let return_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with func_node, "return_type"
    If return_type is not equal to 0:
        Let type_len be proc string_length from StringCore with return_type
        If type_len is greater than 0:
            proc emit with ctx, ": "
            proc emit with ctx, return_type
        End If
    End If
    
    proc emit with ctx, "\n"
    
    Let body be proc hir_function_get_body from HIR with func_node
    proc generate_statement with ctx, body
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits the comma-separated parameter list for a function or method.
PHP supports optional type hints on parameters since PHP 5; this
generator emits the type hint (when non-empty) followed by the
parameter name. No default-value or by-reference handling is provided
here; if needed those would extend this routine without changing its
caller.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops over hir_function_get_parameters. For each: queries the type
via hir_parameter_get_type; if the type string is non-empty emits
"TYPE " (with trailing space). Emits the parameter name. Adds ", "
between consecutive parameters (not after the last).
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_parameters" takes ctx as Integer, func_node as Integer:
    Let parameters be proc hir_function_get_parameters from HIR with func_node
    Let param_count be proc list_length from ListCore with parameters
    Let i be 0
    
    While i is less than param_count:
        Let param be proc list_get from ListCore with parameters, i
        
        Note: Type hint
        Let param_type be proc hir_parameter_get_type from HIR with param
        If param_type is not equal to 0:
            Let type_len be proc string_length from StringCore with param_type
            If type_len is greater than 0:
                proc emit with ctx, param_type
                proc emit with ctx, " "
            End If
        End If
        
        Note: Parameter name
        Let param_name be proc hir_parameter_get_name from HIR with param
        proc emit with ctx, param_name
        
        If i is less than param_count minus 1:
            proc emit with ctx, ", "
        End If
        
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: STATEMENT GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Statement-level dispatch. Reads the HIR node's type tag and routes to
the specialist generator (block, if, while, for, return, break,
continue). Anything not matched is treated as an expression statement
- the routine emits indentation, the expression, and the trailing
';\n'. Null nodes return immediately so callers can pass optional
clauses without null-checking.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null stmt_node short-circuits via Return. Reads hir_node_get_type;
cascade of equality tests against HIR.HIR_BLOCK / _IF / _WHILE / _FOR
/ _RETURN dispatches to the corresponding generate_* and returns.
HIR.HIR_BREAK and HIR.HIR_CONTINUE emit single-line "break;" /
"continue;" with proper indentation. Default path: emit_indent,
generate_expression, ";\n".
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_statement" takes ctx as Integer, stmt_node as Integer:
    If stmt_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    
    Let stmt_type be proc hir_node_get_type from HIR with stmt_node
    
    Note: Block
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BLOCK:
        proc generate_block with ctx, stmt_node
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: If statement
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_IF:
        proc generate_if_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: While loop
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_WHILE:
        proc generate_while_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: For loop
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FOR:
        proc generate_for_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: Return statement
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_RETURN:
        proc generate_return_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: Break
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BREAK:
        proc emit_indent from ctx
        proc emit with ctx, "break;\n"
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: Continue
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CONTINUE:
        proc emit_indent from ctx
        proc emit with ctx, "continue;\n"
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: Expression statement
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc generate_expression with ctx, stmt_node
    proc emit with ctx, ";\n"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a PHP brace-delimited block. The open brace appears on its own
indented line per Allman style; the indent is increased while emitting
the body so nested statements line up correctly; the close brace
returns to the outer indent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
emit_indent + "{\n". increase_indent. Iterates hir_block_get_statements,
recursing into generate_statement for each. decrease_indent.
emit_indent + "}\n".
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_block" takes ctx as Integer, block_node as Integer:
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "{\n"
    
    proc increase_indent from ctx
    
    Let statements be proc hir_block_get_statements from HIR with block_node
    Let stmt_count be proc list_length from ListCore with statements
    Let i be 0
    
    While i is less than stmt_count:
        Let stmt be proc list_get from ListCore with statements, i
        proc generate_statement with ctx, stmt
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    
    proc decrease_indent from ctx
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "}\n"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a PHP if/else construct. Branches that are already
HIR_BLOCK pass through generate_statement which adds its own braces;
branches that are bare statements are wrapped in synthesised braces
to satisfy PHP's grammar uniformly. The 'else if' chain is realised
by recursing into generate_if_statement at one fewer indent level so
the conditional sits on the same line as 'else'.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits 'if (CONDITION) '. Reads then_branch and inspects its HIR
type: HIR_BLOCK -> emit "\n" then generate_statement (which produces
the brace block); otherwise emit "{\n", increase_indent,
generate_statement, decrease_indent, emit_indent + "}\n". Reads
else_branch; if non-null emits 'else '; if else_branch is HIR_IF
chain-recurses (temporarily decrementing indent_level to keep the
'else if' on one line); HIR_BLOCK delegates; otherwise synthesised
braces as above.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_if_statement" takes ctx as Integer, if_node as Integer:
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "if ("
    
    Let condition be proc hir_if_get_condition from HIR with if_node
    proc generate_expression with ctx, condition
    
    proc emit with ctx, ") "
    
    Let then_branch be proc hir_if_get_then from HIR with if_node
    Let then_type be proc hir_node_get_type from HIR with then_branch
    
    If then_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BLOCK:
        proc emit with ctx, "\n"
        proc generate_statement with ctx, then_branch
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with ctx, "{\n"
        proc increase_indent from ctx
        proc generate_statement with ctx, then_branch
        proc decrease_indent from ctx
        proc emit_indent from ctx
        proc emit with ctx, "}\n"
    End If
    
    Let else_branch be proc hir_if_get_else from HIR with if_node
    If else_branch is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_indent from ctx
        proc emit with ctx, "else "
        
        Let else_type be proc hir_node_get_type from HIR with else_branch
        
        If else_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BLOCK:
            proc emit with ctx, "\n"
            proc generate_statement with ctx, else_branch
        Otherwise:
            If else_type is equal to HIR.HIR_IF:
                Note: else if
                proc emit with ctx, ""
                Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level minus 1
                proc generate_if_statement with ctx, else_branch
                Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level plus 1
            Otherwise:
                proc emit with ctx, "{\n"
                proc increase_indent from ctx
                proc generate_statement with ctx, else_branch
                proc decrease_indent from ctx
                proc emit_indent from ctx
                proc emit with ctx, "}\n"
            End If
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a PHP while loop. The body brace handling mirrors
generate_if_statement: HIR_BLOCK bodies pass through directly; bare-
statement bodies get synthesised braces. PHP's do-while form is not
covered here because the bootstrap HIR does not surface it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits 'while (CONDITION) '. Inspects body's HIR type: HIR_BLOCK ->
emit "\n" + generate_statement; otherwise synthesised brace form
with proper increase_indent/decrease_indent bracketing.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_while_statement" takes ctx as Integer, while_node as Integer:
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "while ("
    
    Let condition be proc hir_while_get_condition from HIR with while_node
    proc generate_expression with ctx, condition
    
    proc emit with ctx, ") "
    
    Let body be proc hir_while_get_body from HIR with while_node
    Let body_type be proc hir_node_get_type from HIR with body
    
    If body_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BLOCK:
        proc emit with ctx, "\n"
        proc generate_statement with ctx, body
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with ctx, "{\n"
        proc increase_indent from ctx
        proc generate_statement with ctx, body
        proc decrease_indent from ctx
        proc emit_indent from ctx
        proc emit with ctx, "}\n"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a C-style PHP 'for (init; cond; update) body' loop. Each of
init, cond, and update is optional; missing clauses simply emit the
';' separator with nothing before. PHP's foreach form is not
generated here - the HIR pipeline lowers iteration to either while
or for prior to PHP emission.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits 'for ('. Reads init/condition/update via the corresponding HIR
accessors; each non-null clause is generated as an expression. The
two ';' separators are unconditionally emitted between clauses. Body
is emitted with the same HIR_BLOCK-or-synthesised-brace pattern used
for if/while.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_for_statement" takes ctx as Integer, for_node as Integer:
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "for ("
    
    Let init be proc hir_for_get_init from HIR with for_node
    If init is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_expression with ctx, init
    End If
    
    proc emit with ctx, "; "
    
    Let condition be proc hir_for_get_condition from HIR with for_node
    If condition is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_expression with ctx, condition
    End If
    
    proc emit with ctx, "; "
    
    Let update be proc hir_for_get_update from HIR with for_node
    If update is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_expression with ctx, update
    End If
    
    proc emit with ctx, ") "
    
    Let body be proc hir_for_get_body from HIR with for_node
    Let body_type be proc hir_node_get_type from HIR with body
    
    If body_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BLOCK:
        proc emit with ctx, "\n"
        proc generate_statement with ctx, body
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with ctx, "{\n"
        proc increase_indent from ctx
        proc generate_statement with ctx, body
        proc decrease_indent from ctx
        proc emit_indent from ctx
        proc emit with ctx, "}\n"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits 'return [expr];'. The value expression is optional - bare
'return;' produces only the keyword. PHP accepts both forms; the
choice depends on the function's return semantics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
emit_indent + 'return'. Reads hir_return_get_value; if non-null emits
" " + generate_expression. Terminates with ";\n".
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_return_statement" takes ctx as Integer, return_node as Integer:
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "return"
    
    Let value be proc hir_return_get_value from HIR with return_node
    If value is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with ctx, " "
        proc generate_expression with ctx, value
    End If
    
    proc emit with ctx, ";\n"
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: EXPRESSION GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Expression-level dispatch. Reads the HIR expression's type tag and
routes to the dedicated generator. Leaf kinds (variables, identifiers)
are inlined here for brevity because they reduce to a single emit
call; complex kinds delegate. Unknown kinds fall through silently
(no emit) which is the right behaviour for forward-compatible HIR
extensions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null expr_node short-circuits. Reads hir_node_get_type. Cascade:
HIR_LITERAL -> generate_literal. HIR_VARIABLE / HIR_IDENTIFIER ->
read name accessor and emit directly. HIR_BINARY_OP / _UNARY_OP /
_TERNARY / _ASSIGN / _CALL / _NEW / _MEMBER_ACCESS / _INDEX_ACCESS /
_ARRAY -> delegate to corresponding generate_* and return.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_expression" takes ctx as Integer, expr_node as Integer:
    If expr_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    
    Let expr_type be proc hir_node_get_type from HIR with expr_node
    
    Note: Literal
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LITERAL:
        proc generate_literal with ctx, expr_node
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: Variable
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_VARIABLE:
        Let var_name be proc hir_variable_get_name from HIR with expr_node
        proc emit with ctx, var_name
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: Identifier
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER:
        Let id_name be proc hir_identifier_get_name from HIR with expr_node
        proc emit with ctx, id_name
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: Binary operation
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BINARY_OP:
        proc generate_binary_op with ctx, expr_node
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: Unary operation
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_UNARY_OP:
        proc generate_unary_op with ctx, expr_node
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: Ternary
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_TERNARY:
        proc generate_ternary with ctx, expr_node
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: Assignment
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_ASSIGN:
        proc generate_assign with ctx, expr_node
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: Call
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL:
        proc generate_call with ctx, expr_node
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: New
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_NEW:
        proc generate_new with ctx, expr_node
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: Member access
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_MEMBER_ACCESS:
        proc generate_member_access with ctx, expr_node
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: Index access
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_INDEX_ACCESS:
        proc generate_index_access with ctx, expr_node
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: Array
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_ARRAY:
        proc generate_array with ctx, expr_node
        Return
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a literal value as PHP source. Strings are wrapped in double
quotes (PHP interprets escapes in double-quoted strings, so callers
relying on literal-string semantics must ensure the lexeme is
already escape-safe). null becomes the PHP 'null' keyword. All other
literal types (numbers, booleans) emit their raw lexeme verbatim.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads literal_type and literal_value via the HIR accessors. If
literal_type equals "string": emit '"', value, '"'. If "null": emit
'null'. Otherwise emit value as-is (which covers number, bool, etc).
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_literal" takes ctx as Integer, literal_node as Integer:
    Let literal_type be proc hir_literal_get_type from HIR with literal_node
    Let literal_value be proc hir_literal_get_value from HIR with literal_node
    
    Let is_string be proc string_equals from StringCore with literal_type, "string"
    If is_string is equal to 1:
        proc emit with ctx, "\""
        proc emit with ctx, literal_value
        proc emit with ctx, "\""
        Return
    End If
    
    Let is_null be proc string_equals from StringCore with literal_type, "null"
    If is_null is equal to 1:
        proc emit with ctx, "null"
        Return
    End If
    
    Note: Number or boolean
    proc emit with ctx, literal_value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a binary operation '(LEFT OP RIGHT)'. Parentheses are emitted
unconditionally so the result is correct without consulting PHP
operator precedence; this trades terseness for unambiguous semantics.
The operator string is HIR-supplied (no PHP-specific translation
needed for the common arithmetic/logical/comparison operators).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "(". Reads left via hir_binary_op_get_left, recurses
generate_expression. Emits " OP " (operator from
hir_binary_op_get_operator). Reads right, recurses. Emits ")".
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_binary_op" takes ctx as Integer, binary_node as Integer:
    proc emit with ctx, "("
    
    Let left be proc hir_binary_op_get_left from HIR with binary_node
    proc generate_expression with ctx, left
    
    proc emit with ctx, " "
    
    Let operator be proc hir_binary_op_get_operator from HIR with binary_node
    proc emit with ctx, operator
    
    proc emit with ctx, " "
    
    Let right be proc hir_binary_op_get_right from HIR with binary_node
    proc generate_expression with ctx, right
    
    proc emit with ctx, ")"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a unary operator either in prefix form (OP OPERAND) or postfix
form (OPERAND OP) based on the 'prefix' metadata flag. This covers
both PHP prefix ops (!, -, ++X) and postfix ops (X++, X--).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads operator and 'prefix' metadata. If prefix=1 emits operator
before operand. Recurses into generate_expression on the operand. If
prefix!=1 emits operator after operand.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_unary_op" takes ctx as Integer, unary_node as Integer:
    Let operator be proc hir_unary_op_get_operator from HIR with unary_node
    
    Note: Check if prefix or postfix
    Let is_prefix be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with unary_node, "prefix"
    
    If is_prefix is equal to 1:
        proc emit with ctx, operator
    End If
    
    Let operand be proc hir_unary_op_get_operand from HIR with unary_node
    proc generate_expression with ctx, operand
    
    If is_prefix is not equal to 1:
        proc emit with ctx, operator
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a parenthesised ternary '(C ? T : E)'. As in generate_binary_op,
parentheses are unconditional so the emitted PHP is correct without
operator-precedence awareness in the caller.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "(". Generates condition. Emits " ? ". Generates then-branch.
Emits " : ". Generates else-branch. Emits ")".
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_ternary" takes ctx as Integer, ternary_node as Integer:
    proc emit with ctx, "("
    
    Let condition be proc hir_ternary_get_condition from HIR with ternary_node
    proc generate_expression with ctx, condition
    
    proc emit with ctx, " ? "
    
    Let then_expr be proc hir_ternary_get_then from HIR with ternary_node
    proc generate_expression with ctx, then_expr
    
    proc emit with ctx, " : "
    
    Let else_expr be proc hir_ternary_get_else from HIR with ternary_node
    proc generate_expression with ctx, else_expr
    
    proc emit with ctx, ")"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits 'TARGET OP VALUE' where OP is the assignment-class operator
('=', '+=', '-=', '*=', etc.). This is reused for compound assignments
which lets the caller carry the operator on the HIR node without
generating distinct HIR kinds for each variant.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Generates target expression. Emits " OP " (operator string from
hir_assign_get_operator). Generates value expression. No surrounding
parentheses (assignment binds tighter than statement boundaries; the
caller is responsible for any wrapping needed in expression context).
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_assign" takes ctx as Integer, assign_node as Integer:
    Let target be proc hir_assign_get_target from HIR with assign_node
    proc generate_expression with ctx, target
    
    proc emit with ctx, " "
    
    Let operator be proc hir_assign_get_operator from HIR with assign_node
    proc emit with ctx, operator
    
    proc emit with ctx, " "
    
    Let value be proc hir_assign_get_value from HIR with assign_node
    proc generate_expression with ctx, value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a PHP function call. The 'php_echo' metadata flag opts the
call into PHP's special 'echo' construct (which is a language form,
not a function, and takes a comma-separated argument list without
parentheses). All other calls use the conventional NAME(arg, ...)
syntax.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads function_name. Reads php_echo metadata; if equal to "true",
emits 'echo ' and the comma-separated arguments WITHOUT surrounding
parentheses. Otherwise emits NAME, '(', the comma-separated
arguments, ')'. In both branches arguments are iterated via
hir_call_get_arguments and recursively generated.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_call" takes ctx as Integer, call_node as Integer:
    Let function_name be proc hir_call_get_name from HIR with call_node
    
    Note: Check if this is a PHP echo
    Let is_echo be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with call_node, "php_echo"
    Let is_echo_true be proc string_equals from StringCore with is_echo, "true"
    
    If is_echo_true is equal to 1:
        proc emit with ctx, "echo "
        
        Let arguments be proc hir_call_get_arguments from HIR with call_node
        Let arg_count be proc list_length from ListCore with arguments
        Let i be 0
        
        While i is less than arg_count:
            Let arg be proc list_get from ListCore with arguments, i
            proc generate_expression with ctx, arg
            
            If i is less than arg_count minus 1:
                proc emit with ctx, ", "
            End If
            
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with ctx, function_name
        proc emit with ctx, "("
        
        Set arguments to proc hir_call_get_arguments from HIR with call_node
        Set arg_count to proc list_length from ListCore with arguments
        Set i to 0
        
        While i is less than arg_count:
            Set arg to proc list_get from ListCore with arguments, i
            proc generate_expression with ctx, arg
            
            If i is less than arg_count minus 1:
                proc emit with ctx, ", "
            End If
            
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        
        proc emit with ctx, ")"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a PHP object construction 'new ClassName(args...)'. The class
name is captured at HIR construction time and emitted verbatim;
qualified class names (with namespace separators) are passed through
without further transformation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits 'new '. Reads class name and emits it. Emits '('. Iterates
hir_new_get_arguments, recursively generating each and separating
with ", ". Emits ')'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_new" takes ctx as Integer, new_node as Integer:
    proc emit with ctx, "new "
    
    Let class_name be proc hir_new_get_class from HIR with new_node
    proc emit with ctx, class_name
    proc emit with ctx, "("
    
    Let arguments be proc hir_new_get_arguments from HIR with new_node
    Let arg_count be proc list_length from ListCore with arguments
    Let i be 0
    
    While i is less than arg_count:
        Let arg be proc list_get from ListCore with arguments, i
        proc generate_expression with ctx, arg
        
        If i is less than arg_count minus 1:
            proc emit with ctx, ", "
        End If
        
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    
    proc emit with ctx, ")"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits an object-property access OBJECT->MEMBER. PHP uses the '->'
arrow for both property reads and method calls; this generator
unconditionally emits '->' for member access. Static class access
(Class::member) is not handled here - it would need a separate HIR
kind because the syntactic form differs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Generates the object expression. Emits '->'. Emits the member_name
verbatim (no escaping or quoting).
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_member_access" takes ctx as Integer, member_node as Integer:
    Let object be proc hir_member_access_get_object from HIR with member_node
    proc generate_expression with ctx, object
    
    proc emit with ctx, "->"
    
    Let member_name be proc hir_member_access_get_member from HIR with member_node
    proc emit with ctx, member_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits an array/index subscript ARRAY[INDEX]. Works for both
positional (numeric) and associative (string-keyed) PHP arrays
because the syntax is identical.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Generates the array expression. Emits '['. Generates the index
expression. Emits ']'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_index_access" takes ctx as Integer, index_node as Integer:
    Let array be proc hir_index_access_get_array from HIR with index_node
    proc generate_expression with ctx, array
    
    proc emit with ctx, "["
    
    Let index be proc hir_index_access_get_index from HIR with index_node
    proc generate_expression with ctx, index
    
    proc emit with ctx, "]"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a PHP array literal '[a, b, c]'. The PHP 5.4+ short array
syntax is used unconditionally; the older 'array(...)' form is not
generated. Associative array elements (key => value) would require
extending this routine with HIR support for keyed entries; the
current bootstrap pipeline only produces positional arrays.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits '['. Iterates hir_array_get_elements; each element is
recursively generated and separated by ", ". Emits ']'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_array" takes ctx as Integer, array_node as Integer:
    proc emit with ctx, "["
    
    Let elements be proc hir_array_get_elements from HIR with array_node
    Let elem_count be proc list_length from ListCore with elements
    Let i be 0
    
    While i is less than elem_count:
        Let elem be proc list_get from ListCore with elements, i
        proc generate_expression with ctx, elem
        
        If i is less than elem_count minus 1:
            proc emit with ctx, ", "
        End If
        
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    
    proc emit with ctx, "]"
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: OUTPUT UTILITIES
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The fundamental output primitive: appends a chunk of text to the
context's running output string. Every other generate_* routine
flows its output through here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sets ctx.output to the StringCore concatenation of ctx.output and
text. The concat allocates a fresh string each call; this is O(N)
per emission but acceptable for the bootstrap's small input sizes.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit" takes ctx as Integer, text as Integer:
    Set ctx.output to proc string_concat from StringCore with ctx.output, text
End Process

@Reasoning:
Writes four spaces times the current indent_level so the next emit
lands at the correct column. Uses four-space indents (PSR-12 PHP
style); changing this width is a single literal-change in this proc.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loop 0..ctx.indent_level: each iteration emits a four-space string.
No-op at indent_level 0 (module scope).
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_indent" takes ctx as Integer:
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than ctx.indent_level:
        proc emit with ctx, "    "
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bumps the context's indent counter so subsequent emit_indent calls
produce one more level of indentation. Paired with decrease_indent
around any nested block.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
ctx.indent_level += 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "increase_indent" takes ctx as Integer:
    Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Companion to increase_indent: drops one level of nesting. The caller
is responsible for never calling this below 0 (which would produce
negative indentation); the convention is that every generator that
calls increase_indent immediately pairs it with decrease_indent on
every exit path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
ctx.indent_level -= 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "decrease_indent" takes ctx as Integer:
    Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level minus 1
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PUBLIC API
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public entry-point alias for generate_php_from_hir. Provides the
naming convention 'hir_to_<lang>' that the translation pipeline
drivers expect when locating backends by symbol name.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tail-calls generate_php_from_hir with the same hir_module argument.
@End Implementation
Process called "hir_to_php" takes hir_module as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc generate_php_from_hir from hir_module
End Process
